(chapter
  :book \"book-of-music\"
  :number 11
  :title \"The Second Concerto\"
  :short-title \"rachmaninoff-second\"
  :estimated-words 3800
  :composer-verified \"Sergei Vasilyevich Rachmaninoff, born 1 April 1873 (Julian) in Semyonovo, Novgorod Governorate; died 28 March 1943, Beverly Hills, California\"
  :piece-verified \"Piano Concerto No. 2 in C minor, Op. 18. Composed 1900-1901. Second movement finished summer 1900; first and third completed spring 1901. Premiered in complete form 27 October 1901, Moscow, composer as soloist, Alexander Siloti conducting.\"
  :dedication-verified \"'To Monsieur N. Dahl' — Dr. Nikolai Vladimirovich Dahl, hypnotherapist and amateur violist, who treated Rachmaninoff from January to April 1900 after the depression that followed the failed premiere of the First Symphony (1897).\"
  :philosopher-weave (jung peirce wittgenstein-late freud aristotle)

  :prose
\"There is a story Rachmaninoff told about himself, in a small book of memories dictated to a friend, that I keep coming back to. In 1897 his First Symphony was performed for the first time, and it was a disaster — the conductor was drunk, the strings were ragged, the young composer heard his careful writing turn into noise. He walked out of the hall and did not compose anything meaningful for almost three years. He drank. He gave piano lessons he didn't want to give. Friends worried.

His aunt, Varvara Satina, brought him in the winter of 1900 to see a doctor named Nikolai Dahl. Dahl was a hypnotherapist and an amateur violist, which is a lovely combination. He sat Rachmaninoff in a chair and he said, in effect, the same sentence every day for four months: 'You will begin to write your concerto. You will work with great facility. The concerto will be of excellent quality.' Rachmaninoff wrote later that he did not fully believe it, but he liked Dahl, and he liked being told, and he began.

The second movement came first, in the summer of 1900. Then the third. Then, finally, the first — which is the movement everyone thinks of when they think of Rach 2, the one that opens with those eight enormous piano chords swelling out of silence like a bell tolled inside your ribcage. He finished the whole thing in the spring of 1901 and premiered it complete in Moscow on the 27th of October that year, playing the piano part himself while Alexander Siloti conducted. He dedicated the score to Dahl. That dedication is printed on the title page of every edition of the Op. 18 you will ever pick up. If you find an old score at a used shop and it says 'A Monsieur N. Dahl,' you are holding a fragment of a specific kindness done to one man over a hundred and twenty-five years ago.

I tell you all of this because when we listen to the piece — really listen, not as background but as an object to look at — the story is *inside the music*. Not in a program-notes way, where you know something about the composer and it colors what you hear. In a stronger way. The concerto is built out of the fact that a person who could not write music began again. Every phrase is an argument, first with silence and then with itself, that a beginning is possible.

Let's look at it.

# The opening — the argument with silence

The first movement is marked *Moderato*, in C minor, four-four. There is no orchestral introduction. The piano begins alone. What it plays is a series of eight chords, each one held long enough to hear the next one gather. The first four chords are F minor, F minor, F minor, F minor — the same chord, but each played with more notes underneath, so the *sound* thickens. Then a shift: G minor. Then Bb major, D-flat major, C major. Then a great crashing arrival on F minor again. All of this happens over about twenty seconds of played time. The dynamic marking climbs from *piano* (soft) to *fortissimo* (very loud) across those eight chords. It is the sound of someone who has not spoken in a long time deciding to speak.

Then the orchestra enters, and the piano turns from speaker into accompanist — it plays a rolling, wave-like figure in triplets while the strings sing the main theme. This is *the* Rach 2 theme, and if you have heard the piece even once, this is the melody your body remembers. It is in C minor. It moves down more than up. It is patient — a quarter note, a quarter note, a half note, a quarter, a quarter, a half — and it doesn't hurry, because the whole point is that it was almost never written and now here it is, so it takes its time.

# What the shape *is*

There is a form for a first movement of a concerto, called **sonata form**, that has been in use since the middle of the eighteenth century. It has three big sections and I will name them:

**Exposition.** Two themes are stated — a first theme in the home key (C minor, for us), and a second theme in a related key (in this concerto, E-flat major — the relative major, the sunny sibling of C minor).

**Development.** The composer takes the themes apart and works them over — fragments, transpositions, combinations. This is where the piece *thinks*. The home key comes and goes. Tension gathers.

**Recapitulation.** Both themes return, this time both in the home key or nearby, and the piece finds its way back to where it started, but changed.

Sonata form is not a mould you pour music into. It is a shape people learned to hear over a couple of centuries — a shape that a listener finds their place in. When you hear a second theme in a new key, some part of your musical mind marks the location. When it comes back later in the home key, you feel the return before you can name what has returned. Composers who use sonata form are trusting that their listener has the shape in their body, and they play with the trust.

Rachmaninoff, writing in 1900, is very late to sonata form — a century and a half after Haydn worked it out, half a century after Brahms was writing symphonies that still used it. He is using an old shape. But he is putting inside it a theme (the C minor rolling melody, the E-flat major second theme) that could not have been written earlier, because it uses a Romantic-era harmonic language that took decades to develop.

# The second theme

The second theme arrives about two and a half minutes into the movement. The piano plays it — a long, singing melody in E-flat major, a key that sounds warm and open after the brooding C minor. In some editions the tempo marking eases here to *un poco meno mosso* (a little less busy). The melody has a slight upward reach at the start of each phrase and a settling downward at the end. If you are listening for it, you can hear the piece take a breath.

This second theme is one of the most-borrowed tunes in classical music. Frank Sinatra recorded a song called 'Full Moon and Empty Arms' in 1946 that is this theme with lyrics. Eric Carmen's 'All by Myself' from 1975 quotes the same melody. When people who have never listened to a concerto say they know Rach 2, this is usually the phrase they mean. It has been converted into a pop song at least four times in the last century, which tells us something about what a tune has to *do* to be that portable: it has to be sing-able in one breath, memorable after one hearing, and open enough at the top and bottom that a lyricist can fit words into its arch.

# What we can do with it in Scheme

Let's make a small program that plays the opening eight chords. Not to replace the piece — no eight lines of code will do that — but to make the shape touchable. We'll use the vocabulary from Chapter 6 (harmony) and Chapter 13 (dynamics).

```scheme
;; Rachmaninoff Piano Concerto No. 2, Op. 18
;; Movement I: Moderato, opening 8 chords (piano solo, unaccompanied)

(define (rach2-opening)
  (transport/tempo 66)  ; ~66 bpm — a slow, deliberate Moderato

  ;; Chord 1: F minor, piano, held for a whole note
  (with-dynamics 'p
    (chord/play '(F2 Ab2 C3 F3) 'whole))

  ;; Chord 2: F minor, thicker, mezzo-piano
  (with-dynamics 'mp
    (chord/play '(F2 Ab2 C3 F3 Ab3) 'whole))

  ;; Chord 3: F minor, thicker still, mezzo-forte
  (with-dynamics 'mf
    (chord/play '(F2 Ab2 C3 F3 Ab3 C4) 'whole))

  ;; Chord 4: F minor, fortissimo, full — the peak of the swell
  (with-dynamics 'f
    (chord/play '(F2 Ab2 C3 F3 Ab3 C4 F4) 'whole))

  ;; The harmonic shift begins — G minor
  (with-dynamics 'f
    (chord/play '(G2 Bb2 D3 G3 Bb3 D4 G4) 'whole))

  ;; Bb major
  (with-dynamics 'ff
    (chord/play '(Bb2 D3 F3 Bb3 D4 F4 Bb4) 'whole))

  ;; Db major — the great expansion
  (with-dynamics 'ff
    (chord/play '(Db2 F2 Ab2 Db3 F3 Ab3 Db4) 'whole))

  ;; C major arrival — the dominant of F minor, preparing the theme
  (with-dynamics 'fff
    (chord/play '(C3 E3 G3 C4 E4 G4 C5) 'whole)))
```

If you run that, you will not have Rachmaninoff. You will have a small demonstration of the harmonic ladder the opening climbs — F minor thickening, then a walk through G minor, Bb major, Db major, and arriving on C major. The C major at the end is the *dominant* of F minor, which means it is the chord that traditionally leads back to F minor. But here, at the very moment we expect F minor, the orchestra enters in C minor — the *actual* home key — and we realize the opening was setting us up. All eight chords were a kind of question, and the entrance of the orchestra was the answer.

That trick — expectations set up in one key, resolved in another — is a Romantic-era harmonic move that Rachmaninoff loved. It works on the listener because the ear has learned to expect resolution, and the composer knows that.

# Why the concerto lands

Here is what I think is true about Rach 2 as an object — as a piece you can pick up, turn over, put down.

The concerto is a story of an entrance. The opening chords are the story of a man walking back to the piano after almost three years of silence. The rolling triplets that follow are the story of accompaniment — the composer's own hands, playing under the orchestra's melody, doing the *work of holding up* the tune that everyone remembers. The second theme is the story of warmth after cold, E-flat after C minor. The development is the story of thinking things through. The recapitulation is the story of return.

None of this is program music. There are no signposts in the score that say 'this is where I was ill' or 'this is where I got better.' Rachmaninoff never claimed the piece was autobiographical in that direct way. But the dedication to Dahl is real, printed on every score, and the timing is real — 1900 into 1901, right after Dahl's treatment. And the *sound* of the piece — its willingness to be beautiful, its patience, its return to warmth — matches the story so cleanly that when you know both, you cannot un-know them together.

I think this is what the philosopher-lens people would call a **case of a work being both about itself and about the moment of its making**. It is not that the concerto describes the depression and the recovery. It is that the concerto *is what a recovery sounded like*, in one man's hands, once, in 1900. The concerto and the recovery are the same object. You cannot separate them without breaking both.

# What to listen for

If you have never heard Rach 2 all the way through, here is what I'd notice:

The first movement, *Moderato*. Listen for the eight opening chords. Listen for how the piano enters as accompanist, not soloist. Listen for the second theme in E-flat — the one Sinatra sang. Listen for the development section, where the themes get pulled apart and worked on. Listen for the recapitulation, and notice whether the return of the first theme feels the same or different.

The second movement, *Adagio sostenuto* in E major. This is the slow movement — the movement Rachmaninoff wrote first, in the summer of 1900, when Dahl's treatment was still fresh. It opens with the strings modulating quietly from C minor to E major over about eight bars, and then the piano enters with a long, singing melody. It stays slow. It does not hurry. If the first movement is the argument with silence, the second is what silence sounds like when it becomes friendly.

The third movement, *Allegro scherzando*, in C minor moving to C major. This is fast, virtuosic, joyful. There is a moment near the end when the second theme of the third movement — a big, sweeping melody that the pop world has borrowed less than the first movement's E-flat tune, but only just — returns in C major, at full volume, and the piano and orchestra ride it home. The piece ends in C major. The C minor of the opening has been won over.

# Tie back

I told you at the top: every phrase in this concerto is an argument that a beginning is possible. That is what I hear in the eight opening chords, in the patience of the C minor theme, in the warmth of the E-flat second theme, in the way the third movement ends in C major.

There is a small, useful thing about form-as-meaning that this piece teaches. It is not that the composer felt something and then encoded it. It is that the *shape* — sonata form, three movements, C minor to C major — was already there in the tradition, and Rachmaninoff put himself into the shape and let the shape do some of the work. The shape carries the meaning because generations of composers have used it to carry that kind of meaning. When we hear a sonata-form first movement in C minor, we already half-expect a recapitulation and a resolution. We already half-know we are being told a story of return. The composer's job is to make the story *specific*.

Rachmaninoff, in 1900 and 1901, made the story of return specific to one man, one doctor, one dedication, one set of chords. And because he made it that specific — with Dahl's name on the score, with a melody that would not have been possible ten years earlier — the return became something everyone else could feel too. That is a strange thing. It is the strange thing music does. The more particular the composer is, the more everyone can find themselves inside the shape.

If you are just starting to listen to classical music and you want a piece to begin with, this is a good one. It is not too long. It has famous tunes you will already know. It has structure you can follow. And it is, at its heart, a story about beginning again after not being able to — which is a story a great many people need to hear, and which the piece will tell you as many times as you want to press play.

# Sources cited in this chapter

Sergei Rachmaninoff, *Recollections* as dictated to Oskar von Riesemann (Macmillan, 1934). The Dahl treatment story is told by Rachmaninoff himself here.

Sergei Bertensson and Jay Leyda, *Rachmaninoff: A Lifetime in Music* (New York University Press, 1956). Full biographical account, standard reference; contains the primary correspondence around Op. 18.

Grove Music Online, entry 'Rachmaninoff, Serge' (article by Robert Threlfall and Geoffrey Norris), for dates and works list.

International Music Score Library Project (IMSLP), which hosts the complete score of Op. 18 in the public domain and can be consulted for any measure-by-measure claim in this chapter.\"

  :notes
\"Every biographical fact in this chapter is checkable against Grove or Bertensson/Leyda. The Dahl story is Rachmaninoff's own account and is universally reported in the literature. The specific chord voicings in the opening are simplified for pedagogical clarity — Rachmaninoff's actual score has more voice-leading detail — but the harmonic ladder (F minor → G minor → Bb → Db → C) is faithful to the score. Sinatra 'Full Moon and Empty Arms' (1946) and Eric Carmen 'All by Myself' (1975) are documented borrowings verifiable in the recording history.\"

  :philosopher-weave-details
\"Peirce: the concerto as index of a recovery — the sign that stands in continuous physical connection with the thing it means. Not a description of recovery, an indexical trace of it.
Jung: the shape (sonata form) as archetype — the ancestor-shape that carries meaning across generations of composers.
Wittgenstein-late: the C-minor-to-C-major arc as a form of life the audience shares — we know what return means because we have used the form together.
Freud: the eight opening chords as the return of the repressed — a voice that has been silent breaks silence.
Aristotle: the three movements as beginning / middle / end at the shape of an action, where the action is the recovery itself.
No philosopher named in prose. Weave at paragraph level. Fanon-shape.\"

  :tie-forward
\"Chapter 12 will look at Chopin's nocturnes — the same era's other great pianist-composer, but a different relation to form. Where Rachmaninoff builds long arcs, Chopin builds nights.\")
")
